## Exercise 05 — Painful Problems

### 📝 Your Answers

**Customer Context:**
> "My ideal reader/customer is someone who loves fantasy, mythology, and gaming deeply — often secretly — and is either on their own creative journey or wishes they were. They take things more seriously than the people around them and haven't found their people yet."

**Final Pain List:**
1. I'm ashamed to admit how deep my love for fantasy and gaming goes — I hide it from people I care about
2. I've been working alone on something only I can see for years and don't know if anyone will ever care
3. I'm tormented by a creative dream but too afraid to say it out loud or start — because then I can fail and people will know
4. I feel like an outsider everywhere — I see the world differently, take things more seriously, and can't find my people
5. I use AI in my creative process and I'm ashamed — I think people will dismiss my work because of it
6. It feels too late. The dream won't leave me alone but life has gotten in the way
7. I went all in and it didn't work. I've lost support. I'm still going but barely
8. I keep getting disappointed by contemporary fantasy — unfinished series, non-serious work
9. The scale of what I want feels delusional — too much to ask for, too much to declare

**Cost of Inaction (top 5):**
1. **Afraid to say the dream out loud** — the dream dies quietly. You spend the rest of your life wondering what would have happened if you'd just declared it.
2. **Went all in and it didn't work** — you quit right before the turn. The work was real but the loneliness wins.
3. **It feels too late** — you trade the dream for comfort and spend your later years in regret.
4. **Working alone on something only I can see** — the work disappears with you. No one ever knew it existed.
5. **Can't find my people** — you keep performing belonging in rooms that were never yours and never feel truly seen.

